english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Simplicity
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer of the year Xinwei, I was staying in Yangchon when the monk Huizhen came seeking instruction. Delighted by his arrival, I inquired whom he had studied under, and learned it was the Secretary Kim, a gentleman of rectitude and erudition, refined in both learning and manner. Since Huizhen had attended his teachings, I could discern his character and received him without hesitation. Observing his conduct—it is pure and cautious; hearing his words—they are concise and apt. He studies with great diligence and shows steady progress, seeking only righteousness while remaining indifferent to profit. Truly, one can see in him the fruits of studying in the Kim household.

    One day, he asked me to name his dwelling. I called it the Hall of Simplicity. When he inquired its meaning, I replied: "Simplicity is the opposite of cunning. Those who practice clever deception know no shame, and shamelessness is humanity's gravest affliction. When others pursue profit through cunning advancement, I who know shame and hold to righteousness—this is simplicity. When others delight in deceit and craftiness, I who know shame and preserve what is true—this too is simplicity. Simplicity is what others abandon but I embrace.

    Yet those who advance do not necessarily succeed, nor do the cunning necessarily accomplish their aims. Their spirits labor endlessly, wearying themselves to no purpose. Why abandon what is genuine within me to seek profit through cunning and falsehood? But those who advance in righteousness while preserving truth gain something of themselves and lose nothing. Thus, without craving, they find peace; without shame, they find ease. This is the way of simplicity—it begins in knowing shame and culminates in transcending shame entirely. In this way one stands vast and whole, lacking nothing. Therefore, to cultivate simplicity is to cultivate virtue."

    Hearing this, Huizhen bowed respectfully and said, "I shall honor these teachings morning and night, never forgetting them." Thus I write this record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yangchon (陽村): The author''s residence during his retirement from court service.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Hall of Simplicity (拙齋): A philosophical concept emphasizing the virtue of knowing shame and preserving truth over worldly cunning and ambition.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Secretary Kim (秘書金公): An esteemed scholar and mentor, whose moral example influences both Huizhen and the author''s understanding of virtue.'
